body:
@paulcbetts I understand your point, and I agree that this is a big concern.
The cleaner way to fix this would be to creates new API methods and deprecates old ones which allow the change without breaking old usage

If it is not worth considering, adding a notice on the documentation page would be fine

@zcbenz, what about moving `appData` and `userData` to `%LOCALAPPCACHE%` like in Chrome and Chromium (see  the comments above by @felicienfrancois and @jorangreef)?

I think we should change the [code](https://github.com/atom/electron/blob/01d2765e4b566df853cd583006ebc7993d48cd38/atom/browser/lib/init.coffee#L93-L94), so we will first test if the `userData` folder exists under `%APPDATA%`, if it does we won't change anything, if it doesn't (meaning it's a new install), we will use `%LOCALAPPDATA%`. That way, we won't break the experience of current users and slowly everyone will move to the new location.

Roaming should be avoided since each enterprise uses different quotas and some times they are just ridiculously low. If a developer wants the data to be synchronized between installs, he/she should use some server side mechanism and not rely on roaming (of course, they can still use `app.setPath()` to change it back, if they really need roaming).

@nxrighthere here my workaround code:

```
var app = require("app");
var path = require("path");
if (process.platform == "win32") {
    app.setPath("appData", process.env.LOCALAPPDATA);
    app.setPath("userData", path.join(process.env.LOCALAPPDATA, app.getName()));
}
```
